<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,834,2014]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,409,1629,1654]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Color in alcohol.</emphasis>
Plain black, gray or dark brown, sometimes with darker spots. Degree of spotting or vermiculations varies among populations, and among individuals of same population. Specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1300,1389,1666,1689]" name="Panama" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Panama</collectingCountry>
and Atrato River (
<figureCitation box="[314,384,1701,1725]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,737,760]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,715]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,716]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Ancistrus centrolepis CIUA 227 in dorsal view from the Atrato River, a Caribbean drainage of northern Colombia; shows dark color phase." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219661/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">
Fig. 
<number box="[369,384,1701,1725]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
) have very few dark spots and those from Baudó River in Pacific 
<collectingCountry box="[1168,1278,1701,1725]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Colombia</collectingCountry>
most heavily spotted (
<figureCitation box="[249,319,1737,1761]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1499,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1477]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1478]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ancistrus centrolepis IMCN 1445 Río San Juan, Colombia (type locality)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219660/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">
Fig. 
<number box="[303,319,1737,1761]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Spots on fins more conspicuous than those on body in many specimens. Spots on the dorsal fin often consist of oblique dashes on membranes. See ‘Remarks’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="353" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,834,2014]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1809,1834]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Distribution.</emphasis>
Pacific drainages of southeast 
<collectingCountry box="[697,786,1810,1833]" name="Panama" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Panama</collectingCountry>
(Bayano and Tuira river drainages) and 
<collectingCountry box="[1237,1347,1809,1833]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(Chocó Region San Juan, Dagua, and Baudó rivers), and the Atrato River basin, which empties into the Caribbean Sea in northwest 
<collectingCountry box="[268,378,1881,1905]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[394,463,1881,1905]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1238,1261]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,240,1204]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,223,1216]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distributions of trans-Andean Ancistrus. Symbols may represent more than one collection. Open symbols indicate type localities." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219659/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">
Fig. 
<number box="[446,463,1881,1905]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="354" pageId="10" pageNumber="353" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,834,2014]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1437,151,608]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="354" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1918,1942]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">Remarks.</emphasis>
Besides differences observed among specimens from different drainages, age, method and state of preservation also contribute to variability observed in pigmentation patterns that led to several species being described. For example, although Eigenmann (
<number box="[676,734,1989,2013]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353" value="1916.0">1916</number>
) described 
<taxonomicName box="[865,961,1990,2014]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Ancistrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="353" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melas">
<emphasis box="[865,961,1990,2014]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">A. melas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as uniformly blackish, the 
<typeStatus box="[1268,1366,1989,2013]" pageId="10" pageNumber="353">holotype</typeStatus>
today has faint dark spots on the abdomen. Fowler (
<number box="[661,719,151,175]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" value="1945.0">1945</number>
) described two new species from the Baudó River, a small river which drains a coastal mountain range that lies between the San Juan River basin to the south (
<typeStatus box="[1231,1281,188,212]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Ancistrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="centrolepis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">A. centrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the Atrato River to the north where 
<taxonomicName box="[758,915,224,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Ancistrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="centrolepis">
<emphasis box="[758,915,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">A. centrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also present (
<figureCitation box="[1105,1170,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1238,1261]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,240,1204]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,223,1216]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distributions of trans-Andean Ancistrus. Symbols may represent more than one collection. Open symbols indicate type localities." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219659/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">
Fig 
<number box="[1153,1170,223,247]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). Fowler’s descriptions were mostly based upon differences in spotting: 
<taxonomicName authority="Fowler, 1945" authorityName="Fowler" authorityYear="1945" box="[690,959,261,284]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Pristiancistrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eustictus">
<emphasis box="[690,959,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Pristiancistrus eustictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the name erected for the more heavily spotted and spiny individuals and 
<taxonomicName box="[557,786,296,320]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Ancistrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="baudensis">
<emphasis box="[557,786,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Ancistrus baudensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the plain form. In collections with larger series of individuals, we find some fish are uniformly blackish, but others with obscure spots on the fins and sometimes the abdomen. Fishes from the Baudó River fish have a brown or gray base color, and are everywhere covered with dark spots that range from round to oblong, with some running together to form short lines. Specimens from the Atrato can be plain black, or dark with darker spotting (
<figureCitation box="[696,764,439,463]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,737,760]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,715]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,716]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Ancistrus centrolepis CIUA 227 in dorsal view from the Atrato River, a Caribbean drainage of northern Colombia; shows dark color phase." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219661/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">
Fig. 
<number box="[748,764,439,463]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="354" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,608]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,476,500]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Etymology.</emphasis>
Although no explanation for the derivation of the name 
<taxonomicName box="[1008,1131,476,500]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Ancistrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="centrolepis">
<emphasis box="[1008,1131,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">centrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was given in the original description we believe that this species was so named to call attention to the unusually spiny lateral plates, a notable feature of this species, and one that led Fowler (
<number box="[778,836,548,572]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" value="1945.0">1945</number>
) to erect a distinct genus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fowler, 1945" authorityName="Fowler" authorityYear="1945" box="[1131,1296,549,572]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Pristiancistrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1131,1296,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">Pristiancistrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for them. In Latin 
<emphasis box="[217,309,585,608]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">centrum</emphasis>
means “a prickle or sharp point”, and 
<emphasis box="[740,793,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="354">lepis</emphasis>
refers to the plates (Crane 
<number box="[1096,1156,583,607]" pageId="11" pageNumber="354" value="2011.0">2011</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
